text:
Counsel for Plaintiff: Jane Doe
Counsel for Defendant: John Doe

Page/Line Examiner Summary of Testimony Relevance 3/12-15 Jane Doe Plaintiff is a 47-year-old construction worker with 25 years of experience. Background of witness 5/20-25 Jane Doe Plaintiff had no prior ankle problems before the accident. Background of witness 7/8-12 Jane Doe Plaintiff describes climbing a ladder to get tools when the ladder slipped and he fell. Cause and circumstances of incident 9/15-20 Jane Doe Plaintiff believes the ladder slipped because it was not secured at the top. Cause and circumstances of incident 11/2-5 Jane Doe Plaintiff admits he did not inspect the ladder before climbing it, assuming it was safe. Perceptions of fault; potential for contributory negligence 12/18-22 John Doe Plaintiff broke his left ankle in three places as a result of the fall. Damages 15/6-10 Jane Doe Plaintiff is still undergoing physical therapy and has not been able to return to work since the accident. Damages 16/24-28 Jane Doe Plaintiff is in constant pain and unable to perform daily activities as he used to. Damages 18/11-15 Jane Doe Plaintiff admits to doing light work on a side job while on disability. Credibility; potential impact on damages 20/5-8 John Doe Plaintiff acknowledges a discrepancy between his earlier statement and the incident report regarding ladder inspection, admitting he was mistaken in his testimony. Credibility; potential impact on perceptions of fault 25/19-23 John Doe Plaintiff's doctor expects a full recovery but notes it will take time. Prognosis 30/12-16 Jane Doe Plaintiff is hopeful for no long-term complications but acknowledges the possibility of risks. Prognosis
